<a href="http://www.salon.com/mwt/wire/2003/12/01/gay_mom/index.html" target="_blank">http://www.salon.com/mwt/wire/2003/..._mom/index.html</a><br />
<br />
Short story: kid was punished for telling another kid his mother is gay, and the school called his family saying he "said a word so bad they won't repeat it over the phone."  Yeah, these bunch of Hitlers are gonna take "I refuse to salute the American flag" well.<br />
<br />
Make no mistake about it, just because there's no law that says they had to doesn't mean they weren't forced to do it.  That's like saying a robbery victim wasn't forced to give up his wallet because he couldn't just tried to fight the armed assailant.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />I believe if you dislike your country enough not to even pledge to the flag, that you should just leave the country altogether,<hr size="1" /></blockquote>Just because much of America sucks doesn't mean there's a Utopian alternative out there.  Canada doesn't sound bad, but Frenchies and 13 months of winter doesn't appeal to me too much.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />but 8-year-olds obviously don't have that choice.  Until they do, they'll keep on pledging if they choose.  If they grow-up not to like it, that's their perogative and they don't have to say it anymore.  And, sure, people and people and pledges and vows don't mean much to most, it's just the principle.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>Exactly.  It's the principle that was forced upon people.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
