	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>I nominate this thread for Fastest Derailment of the Week. 5 Post and we are into the political implications of the pledge and its effects on 8 year old rugrats.<br />
<br />
I pledge allegiance to the flag of the United States of America and to the republic for which it stands one nation, under God, indivisible with liberty and justice for all.<br />
<br />
If you are a citizen of the US, either 8 or 80, what part of that statement do you object too? The pledge is to the Flag and the Republic not the government. The Flag represents the ideals of this nation. While it has flown over massacres and betrayals it has also flown for freedom and justice. It is not the Flag's fault that those that carry her do not always live up to her ideals. But I, for one, still hold to those ideals even when I can not measure up.<br />
<br />
The Republic is the totality of all the people living within the US. We are not pledging devotion to the President or Congress. We pledge to each other. How can any decent human being not extend this allegiance to his fellow countrymen?<br />
<br />
I respect anyone who stands up and spits in the governent's eye. Anyone that demands our government live up to the ideals that Flag is suppose to represent. But I expect that person to have the best interest of the people of this nation in his heart. Regardless of other differences, be them political, religious, or otherwise, I would call any person my brother (or sister) that could make that pledge and holds its meaning in their heart.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
