</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Bufr</b><br /><i>If you are a citizen of the US, either 8 or 80, what part of that statement do you object too?</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Okay, let's go through it piece by piece.<br />
<br />
"I pledge allegiance to the flag of the United States of America"<br />
<br />
Pfft.  How do you pledge your allegiance to a piece of cloth?  That doesn't even make any damn <i>sense</i>.<br />
<br />
"and to the republic for which it stands"<br />
<br />
I got a big problem here.  I don't pledge jack to the entire country.  I think the majority of this country (as well as the majority of all humanity) are scumbags.  I give my loyalty to single people, not entire countries.  Especially not ones with which I find so much wrong on levels as basic as human rights.<br />
<br />
"one nation, under God,"<br />
<br />
And we start with the religious implications right there.  Personally, I'm a Christian, but I find something wrong with the fact this so-called "dream" can't go a one sentence pledge without showing heavy favortism towards the majority.<br />
<br />
"indivisible with liberty and justice for all."<br />
<br />
That's just downright funny.  This country is EXTREMELY divided.  The people are divided.  Hell, even the states are divided.  We seperate ourselves into FIFTY-ONE basic governments (fifty states and federal), and we call ourselves indivisible?  Yeah, okay.  Liberty?  You obviously have a different conception of liberty.  Mine includes equality.  Justice?  That's the funniest one of all.  We let murders off on legal technicalities, and we let child molestors off because of psychological evaluations.  Don't defile the good name of justice by associating it with the United States of America.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />The pledge is to the Flag and the Republic not the government. The Flag represents the ideals of this nation.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>Whose ideals are those?  The ideals of our forefathers who proclaimed "all men are created equal" before ordering their slave to make dinner and telling their wife she has no voice outside the kitchen?  Maybe the ideals of fascists like Bob Barr and George W Bush, who try to legally attack religions they don't agree with?  There's a million different ideals of what this nation stands for.  Why?  We've made ourselves out to be some kind of dreamland.  "Land of the Free, Home of the Brave."  "Land of Opportunity."  The way America is constantly put on a pedestal makes people think its spirit is "perfect and right."  <i>THEIR</i> version of "perfect and right."<br />
<br />
There is no true "ideals of this nation."  Sorry, it's all in the eye of the beholder.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />The Republic is the totality of all the people living within the US.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>Exactly.  And how many of those people wouldn't get your trust and loyalty individually?  A great number, I'm betting.  Same for most people.  So why make such a broad statement as pledging your support to them all?  It's not like you're encouraging the terrorists by admitting to yourself that you don't like all your countrymen.<br />
<br />
It's wrong to group millions of people together with a negative statement.  They call it stereotyping.  So why is it so great to group millions of people together with an oath of loyalty?<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />We are not pledging devotion to the President or Congress. We pledge to each other. How can any decent human being not extend this allegiance to his fellow countrymen?<hr size="1" /></blockquote>Because there's so many of them that deserve nothing but contempt and hatred.  Pledging allegiance to the entire country is like a massive stereotype.  All blanket statements are wrong. Wait, <i>that</i> was a blanket statement.  ****.  Okay, almost all blanket statements are wrong, and I see no reason this should be different.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />But I expect that person to have the best interest of the people of this nation in his heart. Regardless of other differences, be them political, religious, or otherwise, I would call any person my brother (or sister) that could make that pledge and holds its meaning in their heart.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>Again, whose idea of best interest?  You make it sound a lot simpler than it is.<br />
<br />
At this point I was gonna reply to Millie, but I don't wanna disrespect an otherwise reasonable discussion.  Maybe next time.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
