	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Bufr</b><br /><i>Well allow me to examine the pledge as well...<br />
<br />
"We pledge allegiance to the Flag of the United States of America"<br />
<br />
It is not a peice of cloth. It is a symbol of our nation. And in being a symbol it makes perfect sense to pledge to it.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Fair enough, but why even mention the flag if the nation itself, or rather its citizens are mentioned a few words later?  Either it's totally redundant, or there's another meaning.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />"and to the republic for which it stands"<br />
<br />
No majority of people on the face of the earth, especially in America, are scumbags. The majority of people are decent and kind.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>Let's say you're right.  Let's say, oh, 30% are Millman.  Why vow to support those 75,000,000 *******s?  Again, blanket statements are generally wrong.  And the bigger the blanket statement, the more chance it's wrong.  I find a blanket statement across the entire country pretty damn wrong.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Even if I accept your position that most people are bad how does that free me from my social responsiblities to them?<hr size="1" /></blockquote>LOL.  Let me reverse that.  Why would I have any social responsibilities to them to begin with?  Because they were born in the same country as I was?  Pffft.  Like I give a damn.  I'd kick certain blood relatives of mine into the gutter and walk away chuckling to myself.  I have absolutely no loyalty to anyone based on the luck of the draw of where they and where I happened to be born.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />This part of the pledge is a promise to hold your place in society in the face of tragedy, to take part in her governance, basically to be a good citizen. We are not excused from this responsibility by the failing of others.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>There's nothing in there about being a good citizen, there's crap in there about unwavering loyalty to a piece of cloth, and a giant mass of humanity.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />"one nation, under god"<br />
<br />
We are one nation. Hell I am an atheist so we can strike the 'under god' thing but to state 2 words make a 'heavy favoritism' towards a majority is silly. Something like 98% percent of people believe in some kind of God I think the last 2% can throw the majority a word or two in the pledge. We are already ahead in the game since we do not believe in invisible men.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>Uh-huh.  God is capitalized, did you notice that?  That denotes a name, rather than a title.  Lots of religions worship a god, but not God.  God denotes Christianity, I believe.  I'm not sure about Buddhism and such, but I know several Wiccans and they're quite clear about that.  God as in a name is Christian.  I have a very big problem with the government showing favortism towards one specific religion.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />"indivisible with liberty and justice for all"<br />
<br />
This nation now stands completely indivisible.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>Let's ignore the current situations which are bad enough... I have a question...  Were we indivisible when we split the country into two to partake in a civil war?<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />I stand by our justice systems warts and all!<hr size="1" /></blockquote>The "justice" system is easily the worst part of this country.  The dream has turned into a nightmare, and anyone that can't see...  I don't know whether to pity your ignorance or envy it.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />I will take a jury trial, assumption of innocence, guarantee of council, and protection from unreasonable search and seizure even when those same guarantees are used to free a guilty man.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>There's nothing wrong with a jury trial, or assumption of innocence.  There's no more guarantee of council if John Asscroft feels you don't deserve it.  Protection from unreasonable search is handled wrong.  Rather than reward the criminal by allowing him to go free no matter how horrendous his crime, he should be charged the same and the officer(s) involved in the violation should be very severely punished.  Any system that lets a murderer go free because a cop didn't wait properly for a search warrant can kiss my ass.  Seizure is a funny thing.  You're wrong, actually.  The government can take anything of yours they please if they think you've done something wrong.  They have no obligation to give it back if you're proven innocent, either.  <a href="http://www.lp.org/lpnews/0103/forfeiture.html" target="_blank">http://www.lp.org/lpnews/0103/forfeiture.html</a>  Nice article.  For example it opens with a story of a woman at an airport told she was under arrest because a police dog scratched her luggage.  After searching her luggage, no drugs were found.  However, her life savings, near fourty thousand dollars, was.  She documented where she got the money, and was never even charged with a crime.  They kept her money anyway, and she's still fighting to get it back years later.  Yeah, lots of protection against government theft--er, "seizure."<br />
<br />
Kiss my ass, American "justice" system.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />(Aside, I know of no instance where a pysch eval has turned a trial in a child molester case. I do know that incorrect evaluation have release predators after their time had been served. The ongoing story in SD might be an example.)<hr size="1" /></blockquote>I know it's happened.  It happened to my brother in law after he confessed to molesting my neice for several years.  I personally don't think the kid's ever going to fully recover fom all the psychological damage, she's a mess.  That mother****er was released after the trial... I forget the exact details, but he's banned from going into the usual places... toy stores and the such.  He got probation and/or community service.  Lots, but who gives a damn?  Because he's one of those damn born agains that think no matter they do, as long as they're sorry it's okay and the psychological evaluations concluded there's little chance he'd ever do it again.<br />
<br />
I wasn't at the trial so I can't say I actually heard the judge give the verdict but I was told by family members what happened.  I kind of doubt my own mother told me that just to piss me off though, so I'm quite confident it happened as hard as it was to believe.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Common ideals of America held almost universally by its citizens...<br />
<br />
We have the right to life.<br />
We have the right to happiness.<br />
We have the right to property.<br />
We have the right to be free.<br />
We believe in the individual.<br />
<br />
You can point out disagreement in the application of these ideals but must leave untouched that they are, in general, held by the people of the nation.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>And I suppose Canadians, British, Austrialians, ect. all spit on those ideals?  They're not inheriently American.  And as you say, we all have different ideas of what those entail...  some with very vast differences.  So I don't see it as being a big deal.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
