	<p>I guess this is what you do when you can't form a logical counterargument?  Sounds like somebody lost to me.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>millman</b><br /><i>Sounds like somone is retarded. He can't get it through his skinny head that there is something called patriotism that is inherantly good.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Spoken like a true mindless sheep.<br />
<br />
BTW, the ones failing to comprehend are you.  What you can't comprehend is that my original point was that <b><i><u>REGARDLESS</b></i></u> of the oath itself, it's wrong to make children make such oaths, and the fact it was done thousands of times was salt in the wound.  Saying it's okay because the pledge is good is like saying it was okay to molest a child if they said they'd have consented when they grew up.  This is a basic matter of forcing an adult decision on someone who is not reasonably capable of making such an adult decision.  What about that can you NOT understand?  Can you not understand why children aren't well enough informed or of mature enough mind to make an oath of loyalty?  Or can you not understand why this is important because your word isn't with the scrap paper it's written on?<br />
<br />
...  Or am I barking up the wrong tree?  Maybe you do understand.  Maybe you do understand, and that's exactly why you changed the subject to the actual message of the oath.  You knew you couldn't win on the actual point, so you went on to argue about the speech itself.  Either way, I'm done arguing about that.  If anybody feels like arguing about the other points made, such as the government stealing billions of dollars worth of goods and cash from citizens never even charged with a crime, or the way the government lets criminals of the worst kind go free with slaps on the wrist, feel free.  I'm done going through the words of a ridiculous speech, though.  Frankly I only took up the argument because I thought it'd be a mental challenge for me to find a reasonable way to invalidate most or all of it.  I'm quite satisifed with what I accomplished, so mission accomplished for me.  I made my point, and even if you have a different view you can't invalidate mine so it's pretty pointless.  Argue facts, not opinions.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />He cries about slavery in our early nation,<hr size="1" /></blockquote>No dip****, I made a point that the idea this country was founded on freedom is a lie.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />yet it still was the most free nation on earth at it's birth, the world was an entirely different place.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>I don't know the history of each and every country, and neither do you.  You're talking out your ass and we both know it.  Considering the number of countries there are, and the fact America endorsed everything from slavery to whatever you'd call what they did to women, I don't think it's unlikely that another country at least matched our so-called freedom.<br />
<br />
Even if that weren't true, saying we had more freedom back then is like saying cow **** stinks less than horse ****.  **** is still **** and **** still stinks.  We didn't have freedom.  Period.  As they say, two wrongs don't make a right.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Think he is still just pissed about all the school beatings and the chicks he never got.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>Thanks for proving my next point: you're inferior.  You are completely mentally inferior not just to myself, but everyone else I've met here.  You're the only one who doesn't even try to form a counterargument, and instead spew tired and stale second rate flames.  Even those I don't particularly like or get along with, such as Kilo, try to make a point.  Mindless flaming is a last resort for everyone else, it's a first resort for you.  The world would be a much better place without people like you.  You're not worth my time.  Go away.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
