<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Bufr</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Lurker<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Jul 2003<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>Cerath since your position seems to be having children, unable to truely make an informed decision at their age, recite the pledge is morally wrong. I will address that issue following one small point. The pledge was written around 1900. The indivisible clause of the pledge was written in light of a nation having faced such a terrible hardship, civil war, and endured. <br />
<br />
The position that, regardless of the content of the pledge, having children take the pledge borders on indefensible. If the content of the pledge changed to "I pledge to do my best in school today" there is nothing that you could object too. The content determines the offense here.<br />
<br />
Therefore it seems to me that whether the reciting of the pledge is right is based on two issues. First is there a benefit to society as a whole? Second does the pledge inflict harm upon the children? Both issues need to be considered since either can outweigh the other.<br />
<br />
The pledge does have a benefit to society. While you seem to disagree, the pledge is ALL about citizenship. It is the first step many children take on that journey towards citizenship. While a young child may not understand the full ramification of being a US citizen until adulthood, it is still a concept that in simpler terms they can grasp. There is a country called America. They are her citizens. They will be responsible for the nation when they are grown. The pledge may have a small part to play in the journey to citizenship, but it certainly has benefit to society on the whole.<br />
<br />
On the second issue of harm to a child I would argue the simple interaction of people can limit this to minimun levels. We are not a society of robots forcing compliance. Teachers are, for the most part, caring people. They will treat a child, who has issues with taking the pledge, with an appropriate degree of care and respect. While I am sure some teachers would fail in this regard, again, the majority would not. Considering the limited number of children that would have problems taking the pledge and the still smaller number that would have a teacher that fails to handle the situation appropriately I can not see how emotional harm caused by the pledge outweighs its societal benefits.<br />
<br />
On other issues raised in this thread ...<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />I made a point that the idea this country was founded on freedom is a lie<hr size="1" /></blockquote>Incorrect. While it is true that the US was a slave state it does not change the fact the nation was formed on the principle of freedom. The issue of slavery was debated during the formation of the nation. Unfortunately, practicalitly won over morality. It was more important to forge the nation. This concession, and the subsequent inability of US leaders to deal with the issue of slavery, lead to the bloodiest war in US history.<br />
<br />
(Slavery, by the time of the signing of the US constitution, had been outlawed in Europe. We took a bit of ribbing on the diplomatic front as hypocritical to profess such a love of freedom yet allow the holding of slaves.)<br />
<br />
We were, however, remarkably free for the period, at least compared to our European friends. We had a much more balanced legal system compared to european equivalents. Access to wealth, property, and opportunity was much greater. <br />
<br />
I find the arguement that utopia was not achieved (your **** is still **** comment) unconvincing. As any culture grows it moves at its own pace. To argue that we were not free because we did not treat woman or Africans as equals belies the tremendous strides we actually made. Any journey must have a starting point and you do not arrive at your destination in a single step. On our journey towards a free society there were many rocky periods, many points when fundemental freedoms were yet to be achieved. We are still an incomplete picture of a free society but to focus on that dims the amazing accomplishments we have made.<br />
<br />
On the issue of property seizures, a minor point to start, the protect from unreasonable search and seizure is related to searchs and arrests. The state can not arrest you with out cause. It can not deprive you of property without due process. In the case of property seizure laws, which I ****ing hate, a civil case in brought, as well as, a criminal case. Since the two are separate you could be found not guilty, or the charges dropped, in the criminal case, but have the civil case move forward. In most cases this is not true but there are horror stories. <br />
<br />
Most of these stories come from the late 80s and early 90s. The one you mention about the lady that lost her life savings was from 1989. In 1993 or 1994 4 cases had made there way through the court system. All 4 were lost by the state. This up-ended the current paradigm of seizure law. A series of laws were past in 1995, 1997, and 2000 to refine and limit property seizures.<br />
<br />
Periodically bad laws are passed in all Nations. We live in a nation, however, were you can fight those laws and overturn them. In their earnest to fight the War of Drugs, an exercise in stupidity, law-makers tried to assail the assest of the criminals. This added an other hammer in the arsenal of prosecutors and police. While it looked good on paper in practice it legalized banditry. I am not aware of many egregious abuses of current seizure laws.<br />
<br />
On the issue of council and its denial to 'prisoners of war'. It has never been firmly established who gets to make the determination of who is an 'enemy combatant'. Ashcroft, and the Federal government in general, want enormous leeway in this area. In doing so they can effectively lock up any individual without the normal due process of a criminal proceeding. They can also more effectively fight the war on terror. <br />
<br />
This is an issue moving through the court system. It will be resolved one way or another. While I believe that such power is too great to hand to an authority in a free society I trust our judicary can make a fair and impartial determination on this matter. <br />
<br />
Careth, you seem to place great emphasis on instances of failure or injustice. You lack a fundemental faith in your fellow man. You gravitate towards any available wrong and by its presense negate any available good. You strike me as a glass half empty kinda guy. <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="smile" smilieid="1" /></p>
	
	
	
	
	
