	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Bufr</b><br /><i>Cerath since your position seems to be having children, unable to truely make an informed decision at their age, recite the pledge is morally wrong. I will address that issue following one small point. The pledge was written around 1900. The indivisible clause of the pledge was written in light of a nation having faced such a terrible hardship, civil war, and endured. <br />
<br />
The position that, regardless of the content of the pledge, having children take the pledge borders on indefensible. If the content of the pledge changed to "I pledge to do my best in school today" there is nothing that you could object too. The content determines the offense here.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Not really.  I would still object, perhaps even moreso.  That pledge I would have broken thousands of times, and the same could be said for a great number of people that made it.  Very few people will betray their nation and break the real pledge.  The main focus of my objection is that kids have to stand and place their hands on their heart while staring at a flag.  That is what seperates a simple muttering from a very serious vow.  Even wedding vows, which IMO are the most important vows 99.999% of the population would ever make, don't require more than the pledge of alligence.  Placing your hand on your heart especially shows the incredible importance it should have.  Something like that shouldn't be thrown upon little children as a daily ritual. <blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Therefore it seems to me that whether the reciting of the pledge is right is based on two issues. First is there a benefit to society as a whole? Second does the pledge inflict harm upon the children? Both issues need to be considered since either can outweigh the other.<br />
<br />
The pledge does have a benefit to society. While you seem to disagree, the pledge is ALL about citizenship. It is the first step many children take on that journey towards citizenship. While a young child may not understand the full ramification of being a US citizen until adulthood, it is still a concept that in simpler terms they can grasp. There is a country called America. They are her citizens. They will be responsible for the nation when they are grown. The pledge may have a small part to play in the journey to citizenship, but it certainly has benefit to society on the whole.<br />
<br />
On the second issue of harm to a child I would argue the simple interaction of people can limit this to minimun levels. We are not a society of robots forcing compliance. Teachers are, for the most part, caring people. They will treat a child, who has issues with taking the pledge, with an appropriate degree of care and respect. While I am sure some teachers would fail in this regard, again, the majority would not. Considering the limited number of children that would have problems taking the pledge and the still smaller number that would have a teacher that fails to handle the situation appropriately I can not see how emotional harm caused by the pledge outweighs its societal benefits.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>I only wish all of that were true.  Teachers unjustly punish many children for a variety of things, such as the sickening story earlier from salon.com.  I'll admit though, that's not why I have such contempt for them.  I grew up with a severe case of depression.  It was dreadfully obvious something was very wrong, whether it be a chemical imbalance issue like depression or something like serious abuse at home.  Each year we had three different teachers, and I can't even remember how many years it went on for... and not once did any of them so much as ask if anything was wrong, let alone try to do anything to actually help.  In fact several of them actually treated me worse than the rest of the class because I "wasn't putting any effort into anything."  There was the yearly trip the school councilor, but that was only because despite my beyond-F grades, my standardized testing came back in the "holy ****" range and they wanted to know if I was just failing because the work was too easy to bother with and I needed to go to a different kind of school.  You'd think that alone would've alerted them that there's beyond a doubt something up.  Granted, I may have had just come up with the short end of the stick on the luck of the draw about which teachers I got... but I doubt it given the number of them I went through.  Teachers are not understanding, and they're not caring (or they're INCREDIBLY stupid) as a general rule.  Considering the way patriotism is viewed, I find it hard to believe a reasonable number of those bastards wouldn't have punished kids who ignored the pledge in some way.<br />
<br />
That said, I don't see it having a noteworthy social benefit as you say.  Let's face it, most kids are thinking about video games or the opposite sex while they're doing that pledge.  They're just going through the motions without a thought.  The few that do truly notice it probably aren't lacking in patriotism to begin with.  Remember the D.A.R.E. program?  That thing were the cops came to schools and educated kids about drugs, their dangers, and what to do in situations?  They didn't stop it for lack of funding... they stopped it because it turned out it was actually increasing drug use.  Given the surprising results of D.A.R.E., I'm at best shaky on the benefits of the pledge.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Incorrect. While it is true that the US was a slave state it does not change the fact the nation was formed on the principle of freedom. The issue of slavery was debated during the formation of the nation. Unfortunately, practicalitly won over morality. It was more important to forge the nation. This concession, and the subsequent inability of US leaders to deal with the issue of slavery, lead to the bloodiest war in US history.<br />
<br />
(Slavery, by the time of the signing of the US constitution, had been outlawed in Europe. We took a bit of ribbing on the diplomatic front as hypocritical to profess such a love of freedom yet allow the holding of slaves.)<br />
<br />
We were, however, remarkably free for the period, at least compared to our European friends. We had a much more balanced legal system compared to european equivalents. Access to wealth, property, and opportunity was much greater.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>While a good legal system is good, it has little to do with actual freedom.  I think slavery would be far and away the biggest part of how free a place is, since slavery is the total opposite of freedom.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />I find the arguement that utopia was not achieved (your **** is still **** comment) unconvincing. As any culture grows it moves at its own pace.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>Actually, that wasn't what I meant.  Bad wording I guess.  I meant that a lack of freedom is still a lack of freedom even if the rest of the world isn't free either.  Being the best of the worst isn't something to be proud of.  I didn't mean anything about current day America.  My only issue with freedom in America right now is gay/trans* rights, especially marriage for the former.  The rest of my gripes aren't really about freedom.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />To argue that we were not free because we did not treat woman or Africans as equals belies the tremendous strides we actually made. Any journey must have a starting point and you do not arrive at your destination in a single step. On our journey towards a free society there were many rocky periods, many points when fundemental freedoms were yet to be achieved. We are still an incomplete picture of a free society but to focus on that dims the amazing accomplishments we have made.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>That's a nice speech, but the fact still remains, when white males are the only ones with rights and freedom it's not truly a free country.  It may have been one of the best at the time, but that doesn't change the fact it wasn't free.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />On the issue of property seizures, a minor point to start, the protect from unreasonable search and seizure is related to searchs and arrests. The state can not arrest you with out cause. It can not deprive you of property without due process. In the case of property seizure laws, which I ****ing hate, a civil case in brought, as well as, a criminal case. Since the two are separate you could be found not guilty, or the charges dropped, in the criminal case, but have the civil case move forward. In most cases this is not true but there are horror stories.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>I wish it were just a handful of horror stories.  When several billion are taken, it's more than that.  I checked an older report, and it said 1991 644 million were "seized."  In 1992, seizures look as if they'll likely exceed a billion.  Given those numbers, it looks as if that 2 billion listed in that story was a year number.  I was hoping it was total.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Most of these stories come from the late 80s and early 90s. The one you mention about the lady that lost her life savings was from 1989. In 1993 or 1994 4 cases had made there way through the court system. All 4 were lost by the state. This up-ended the current paradigm of seizure law. A series of laws were past in 1995, 1997, and 2000 to refine and limit property seizures.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>I did a search on these laws.  Only one I found was the 2000 one, and while I don't have time right now to read that huge review (I don't even have the time to be writing this really), it looks as if while the new law helps a bit, the problem is still quite bad.  Even if they fixed it tomorrow, it's too little too late.  They've known about this problem for too long and not fixed it.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Periodically bad laws are passed in all Nations. We live in a nation, however, were you can fight those laws and overturn them. In their earnest to fight the War of Drugs, an exercise in stupidity, law-makers tried to assail the assest of the criminals. This added an other hammer in the arsenal of prosecutors and police. While it looked good on paper in practice it legalized banditry. I am not aware of many egregious abuses of current seizure laws.<br />
<br />
On the issue of council and its denial to 'prisoners of war'. It has never been firmly established who gets to make the determination of who is an 'enemy combatant'. Ashcroft, and the Federal government in general, want enormous leeway in this area. In doing so they can effectively lock up any individual without the normal due process of a criminal proceeding. They can also more effectively fight the war on terror.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>I'm not quite sure either.  I do remember Asscroft trying to get a law passed that gave the attorney general virtually absolute power over that and given the way they got that ridiculous anti-terrorism bill passed, it's not a big stretch.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />This is an issue moving through the court system. It will be resolved one way or another. While I believe that such power is too great to hand to an authority in a free society I trust our judicary can make a fair and impartial determination on this matter.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>I wish I could say the same.  The system has failed too many times when there's no excuse for its failure and IMO it no longer deserves the benefit of the doubt.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Careth, you seem to place great emphasis on instances of failure or injustice. You lack a fundemental faith in your fellow man. You gravitate towards any available wrong and by its presense negate any available good. You strike me as a glass half empty kinda guy. <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="smile" smilieid="1" /><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Quite correct.  I'll freely admit I'm quite the pessimist.  Especially in this instance, I've seen so many failures by the system I can't possibly muster any optimism about the system.  People claim in court, and correctly (though not rightly if that makes sense) that taxes are illegal.  Judges still give them the finger.  Female child molestor winds up pregnant and sued her victim's parents for child support, judge says there's nothing he can do, the law says she gets it.  I just don't see any proof that the U.S. government cares about its own citizens.<br />
<br />
As for humanity as a whole, I do believe the majority feel what they're doing is right.  But you know what they say... the most harm comes from the best intent.  Too many have ideas of good that involve hurting others which are (IMO) innocent.  This is why I have no "faith" in my fellow man.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
