	<!-- message -->
	<p>Ok, first off D.A.R.E, isn't this the program you are saying is dead? <a href="http://www.dare.com" target="_blank">http://www.dare.com</a> Ken Malcolm was named "Officer of the Year". So it seems the organization is still in operation. I am not aware of D.A.R.E increasing drug use, not that I follow it much <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="smile" smilieid="1" /> . If you have a source please cite it. I would like to know more.<br />
<br />
Second you present me with an interesting conumdrum. At one point you state...<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" /> Placing your hand on your heart especially shows the incredible importance it should have. Something like that shouldn't be thrown upon little children as a daily ritual. <hr size="1" /></blockquote>And then later ...<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Let's face it, most kids are thinking about video games or the opposite sex while they're doing that pledge.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>On one hand the pledge is too important, too much ritual for children, but then, later, it is too trivial to be of issue. Allow me to infer your meaning and please correct my mistakes. The pledge is too much for very young children since the ritual of it conotes such importance, facing the flag, on your heart, and the group ascept of everyone reciting at once. A particularly young child, say 12 or less, may object but not have sense of self to challenge his participation. This leads to resentment and bitterness by the child.<br />
<br />
The second statements address children later in life, young adults. Teenagers have their own sets of priorities and Civics and citizenship generally don't top the list. They would simply move through the pledge as mere drudgery.<br />
<br />
Let me address the second issue first. If it is an action in drudgery then let it be. There are plenty of annoying things to do in life, standing in line at the DMV, paying taxes, and baggage claim at airports. All suck major ass. If the action has no meaning to most its presense can not be a great affront, therefore its meaning to the few warrents its continuation. I would still argue that if it could on occasion forced someone to confront the words of the pledge then it is of great social benefit.<br />
<br />
If the pledge is too important or too filled with cermony at certain ages I disagree that this is bad. The pledge is basically stating "I am an American citizen". That is an incredibly important statements. (As is citizenship in any country, especially a democracy.) I can not fathom how, even with its pomp and ceremony, taking the pledge is bad. Even if you don't agree with it.<br />
<br />
The pledge is not an oath. It is not a vow. It is not binding in any manner. If you get married and back out of it you can legally have your property divided between you and your spouse. If you swear an oath and then give false testimony you could then lose your freedom and your property. If you back out of your pledge of allegiance absolutely nothing happens to you. <br />
<br />
On the issues of teachers I grew up around them. My Father was a teacher and my step Mother. Most of there friends were teachers. While I have never seen them around their students they have impressed me of being a caring and compassionate lot. Your interaction with teachers are certainly personal to you. It seems the life has dealt you more than your fair share of body blows. I am sorry that someone, teacher, parent, or otherwise, wasn't able to identify and address the pain you were feeling. Since I do not have some impartial statistic addressing teacher 'caring' rating I will have to disagree with you, our personal observations simply contradict each other.<br />
<br />
You still hold to your negation policy in regards to the nation's origin. Could you concede that Vermont, New Hampshire, Massechusest(sp?), and Maine, since they outlawed slavery before signing the US constitution, embraced freedom? That they did so for broader segment of their population than other nations?  If the "best of the worst" is no good who were the "worst of the best"? Who are these mythical other nations that were more free, that provided greater rights to the common citizen? If you expand "the worst" too broadly then, of the worst quarterbacks to ever play the game, Joe Montana was the best. <br />
<br />
The use of property seizure, while I loathe it, has a legitmate place in the prosecutorial arsenal. It removes vast assests from criminal organizations, however it was too broad and mis-used by police and needed to be curtailed. Not all the 640 million you cite would be abusively seized. Property used to commit a crime can be seized, and in certain cases, should be seized.   <br />
<br />
The problem began in the late 80s with an expansion of a 1979 seizure law. Its hey day lasted thru the ealry 90s, a period of about 6 or 7 years. While any period of injustice is bad it takes a while to shake things out. Seizure laws are not currently that egregious, though I would like an automatic return of property on a not guilty verdict. <br />
<br />
The other issues that we disagree on rely too heavily on opinion to warrent pursuit. My faith in the justice system is not shared by you, so lets just hope for the best.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
