	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Bufr</b><br /><i>Ok, first off D.A.R.E, isn't this the program you are saying is dead? <a href="http://www.dare.com" target="_blank">http://www.dare.com</a> Ken Malcolm was named "Officer of the Year". So it seems the organization is still in operation. I am not aware of D.A.R.E increasing drug use, not that I follow it much <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="smile" smilieid="1" /> . If you have a source please cite it. I would like to know more.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>My apologies, that was my fault.  I made the critical error of actually paying attention to the local news.  While they don't outright lie, let's just say the media in my city doesn't have a huge budget for fact checkers.  It's possible they meant that only happened locally here.  Also possible they were just being idiots.  50/50 chance, I guess.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />On one hand the pledge is too important, too much ritual for children, but then, later, it is too trivial to be of issue. Allow me to infer your meaning and please correct my mistakes. The pledge is too much for very young children since the ritual of it conotes such importance, facing the flag, on your heart, and the group ascept of everyone reciting at once. A particularly young child, say 12 or less, may object but not have sense of self to challenge his participation. This leads to resentment and bitterness by the child.<br />
<br />
The second statements address children later in life, young adults. Teenagers have their own sets of priorities and Civics and citizenship generally don't top the list. They would simply move through the pledge as mere drudgery.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>Not quite.  What I meant at first was that it's a very serious affair in my book and it's not given the proper respect.  By that I mean that it's not given proper respect by the system and the adults, not the children who just go through the motions.  And by the second, I meant all ages, not just particularly teenagers.  I guess I should've rephrased that comment about the opposite sex.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Let me address the second issue first. If it is an action in drudgery then let it be. There are plenty of annoying things to do in life, standing in line at the DMV, paying taxes, and baggage claim at airports. All suck major ass. If the action has no meaning to most its presense can not be a great affront, therefore its meaning to the few warrents its continuation. I would still argue that if it could on occasion forced someone to confront the words of the pledge then it is of great social benefit.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>Perhaps.  My gripe with just letting it be part of the drudgery is that it's not giving it the proper respect.  Anything that involves pledging your life, which is what I assume the hand over the heart has to mean, shouldn't just be part of the routine along with brushing your teeth.  Maybe I'm crazy, but I just think something like the pledge is too important a thing to just be another part of the day.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />If the pledge is too important or too filled with cermony at certain ages I disagree that this is bad. The pledge is basically stating "I am an American citizen". That is an incredibly important statements. (As is citizenship in any country, especially a democracy.) I can not fathom how, even with its pomp and ceremony, taking the pledge is bad. Even if you don't agree with it.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>I'm not saying that.  I'm saying that it should be an incredibly important statement as you say.  Too important to just become part of the routine, and too important to put onto the shoulders of children.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />The pledge is not an oath. It is not a vow. It is not binding in any manner. If you get married and back out of it you can legally have your property divided between you and your spouse. If you swear an oath and then give false testimony you could then lose your freedom and your property. If you back out of your pledge of allegiance absolutely nothing happens to you.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>Those aren't the only kinds of oaths and pledges.  Just because those two hold legal ramifications doesn't mean they all do.  A direct dictionary quote for the defition of "vowing":<br />
<br />
1. To promise solemnly; pledge. See Synonyms at promise.<br />
2. To make a pledge or threat to undertake: vowing revenge on their persecutors.<br />
<br />
The pledge of alligence fits all the standards for either vow or oath and in fact, "pledge," "vow," and "oath" are fairly interchangeable.  It just so happens that the two most well known of vow and oath hold serious legal ramifications if broken.  Think of, say, a priest's vow of celibacy.  That's another well known one.  Yet it doesn't hold any ramifications either legally, or apparently with the church (at least if it's broken with a child, I'm not sure about an adult as sad as that is).<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />On the issues of teachers I grew up around them. My Father was a teacher and my step Mother. Most of there friends were teachers. While I have never seen them around their students they have impressed me of being a caring and compassionate lot. Your interaction with teachers are certainly personal to you. It seems the life has dealt you more than your fair share of body blows. I am sorry that someone, teacher, parent, or otherwise, wasn't able to identify and address the pain you were feeling.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>Ugh.  I didn't mean to come off as whining, and I definitely wasn't looking for pity.  Frankly, I think I'm a better person now because of it.  What doesn't kill you makes you stronger.  I just meant that given my experience with quite a number (rough guess 15-20) they were at best uncaring apathetic souls.  The stories about the teacher that turns a kid's life around is the gem in the rough, not commonplace.  Teachers teach, they don't look out for the overall welfare of the children.  Or at least, quite a number of them are that way even if the majority aren't.  Enough to be dangerous.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Since I do not have some impartial statistic addressing teacher 'caring' rating I will have to disagree with you, our personal observations simply contradict each other.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>True.  I suppose it's a matter which can never be proven one way or the other because no one could have dealt with a large enough sampling for a long enough period of time to make an accurate judgment.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />You still hold to your negation policy in regards to the nation's origin. Could you concede that Vermont, New Hampshire, Massechusest(sp?), and Maine, since they outlawed slavery before signing the US constitution, embraced freedom? That they did so for broader segment of their population than other nations?<hr size="1" /></blockquote>Fair enough.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />If the "best of the worst" is no good who were the "worst of the best"? Who are these mythical other nations that were more free, that provided greater rights to the common citizen? If you expand "the worst" too broadly then, of the worst quarterbacks to ever play the game, Joe Montana was the best.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>Bad phrasing I suppose.  I meant that despite the rest of the world being at least somewhat worse, the US was not free.  Calling the US back then "the land of the free" is like setting up a bunch of cans of black paint of varying shades, picking the lightest shade of black and calling it white.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />The use of property seizure, while I loathe it, has a legitmate place in the prosecutorial arsenal. It removes vast assests from criminal organizations, however it was too broad and mis-used by police and needed to be curtailed. Not all the 640 million you cite would be abusively seized. Property used to commit a crime can be seized, and in certain cases, should be seized.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>It should, but as the statistics say, 80% of people whose property is stolen in that fashion are never even charged with a crime.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
