	<!-- message -->
	<p>The arguement about America centered on it being founded on the principle of freedom. I am happy to concede that not all in America were truely free since this a practical fact. Are you will to concede that, while incomplete, freedom was a founding principle of this nation?<br />
<br />
Pledges, vows, and oath are different. They are not really interchangable. A pledge of celibacy invokes a different connotation than a vow of celibacy. An oath is definitly different as it implies a promise, generally made before a witness, with a penalty for breaking it. <br />
<br />
A vow in the church if broken can be repair by asking forgivness. Focusing on sexual conduct between adults, since I think those pedophilic priests should have been tossed out on their ass and into prison, a priest that breaks his vow is asked to go through a process where he determines if he can hold himself to the vow. If he finds he can not he leaves the church. <br />
<br />
A pledge holds the lowest significance in this word set. You pledge to be a good citizen, you vow to be a good husband, and you take an oath to become President.<br />
<br />
The hand on the heart is a non-military salute. It does not imply a swearing of your life. It is an acknowledgment of respect. It is only used during the pledge and the singing of the National Anthem.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
