	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />1. Children being forced to take an oath every morning like clockwork.<br />
2. People like Ashcroft trying to take away freedoms like the right to an attorney.<br />
3. The government legalizing theft for themselves and then stealing billions from innocent citizens.<br />
4. Letting the worst kinds of criminals such as murderers and child molestors go unpunished.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>Well I will fly into the teeth of this collection of strawman arguements. <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="smile" smilieid="1" /><br />
<br />
1. My only comment on this one is the chuckle I get that replace pledge with oath whenever you can. The pledge is a pledge not a vow or oath. These are the definitions... <br />
<br />
Pledge - a formal or solemn promise or agreement, esp. to do or refrain from doing something<br />
 <br />
Oath - a solemn pronouncement to affirm the truth of a statement or to pledge a person to some course of action, often involving a sacred being or object as witness<br />
<br />
Vow - a solemn or earnest pledge or promise binding the person making it to perform a specified act or behave in a certain way<br />
<br />
If you mean to argue children can not tell the differnence then make that arguement. But your number 1 contention is a factual mistake. They are not forced, though some children might think they are, nor is an oath involve.<br />
<br />
So to rewrite #1 to coincide with facts ...<br />
<br />
We ask children, though some might think they have to, to state that they will be loyal citizens of this nation.<br />
<br />
Number 2<br />
<br />
I am not a fan of Ashcroft or the current administration, however I appreciate the pickle they are in. Confronted with an enemy using tactics and means that this nation has not had to deal with before, they are tasked with protecting the citizens from these enemies. <br />
<br />
While I vehemently disagree with Ashcroft interpretation of enemy combatant laws, I am forced to support his right to make that interpretation. My disagreement, and more importantly those being held, will get their day in court so to speak. Already suits have been filed and are working their way through the courts asking the Judical Branch to better outline the restrictions and ability of the Executive Branch during this War on Terror.<br />
<br />
All nations must respect their own Laws. The citizens of a nation must also respect them. Ashcroft is using a set of Laws designed to address combatants from traditional wars in a new paradigm of warfare, Terrorism. In doing he seems in violation of many important civilian laws, not the least of which right to council and right to a speedy trial. However, there is no great evil here. This matter will be determined by the courts. The history of the courts most often side agianst undue expansion of prosecutorial authority. So I am willing to be patience and see this play out.<br />
<br />
Number 3<br />
<br />
We, the citizens, have legalized seizure of property. It has been voted on in a many states and is generally support by the public as a tool against drug dealers and organized crime. I dispute that billions have been stolen from innocent people. He made a statement that 80% came from people who had charges against them dropped. I have not found anything to support this.<br />
<br />
In many cases, the seizeing of property used in the commission of a felony is justified. If you agree with that statement then your only arguement could be its application. Most of the horror stories, that verge of governmental banditry, occured over 10 years ago. The state had its power curtailed by court rulings in the 90s and the law written as recently as 2000. So why is this such a big deal?<br />
<br />
Number 4<br />
<br />
Murderers must go free to maintain justice in the country. There I said it. I feel better. The fact that a person is guilty can only be determined by 2 things, a jury, or if requested by the defendant, a judge. If evidence is improperly seized or some other 'technicality' violated then that evidence is excluded. Period. If it frees a rapist, though it is horrible, its is less of a sin than giving up our freedoms and civil protections.<br />
<br />
Wulfbane,<br />
<br />
Hey if you know someone making a Utopia society please have them PM me. I ain't proud I will take a nice comfy spot. <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="smile" smilieid="1" /></p>
	
	
	
	
	
