	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Bufr</b><br /><i>Well I will fly into the teeth of this collection of strawman arguements. <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="smile" smilieid="1" /><br />
<br />
1. My only comment on this one is the chuckle I get that replace pledge with oath whenever you can. The pledge is a pledge not a vow or oath. These are the definitions... <br />
<br />
Pledge - a formal or solemn promise or agreement, esp. to do or refrain from doing something<br />
 <br />
Oath - a solemn pronouncement to affirm the truth of a statement or to pledge a person to some course of action, often involving a sacred being or object as witness<br />
<br />
Vow - a solemn or earnest pledge or promise binding the person making it to perform a specified act or behave in a certain way<br />
<br />
If you mean to argue children can not tell the differnence then make that arguement. But your number 1 contention is a factual mistake. They are not forced, though some children might think they are, nor is an oath involve.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>No.  Just plain no.  We've been through this.  I've checked two major brands of dictionaries and they both say the exact same thing: an oath is a pledge.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Number 2<br />
<br />
I am not a fan of Ashcroft or the current administration, however I appreciate the pickle they are in. Confronted with an enemy using tactics and means that this nation has not had to deal with before, they are tasked with protecting the citizens from these enemies.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>Pfft.  There's a lot of of these "anti-terrorism" laws that have nothing to do with terrorism.  In one of those bills they banned credit card companies from knowingly accepting charges from online casinos.  What the hell does a virtual casino have to do with terrorists?  Especially ones based in friendly countries such as Canada?<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />While I vehemently disagree with Ashcroft interpretation of enemy combatant laws, I am forced to support his right to make that interpretation. My disagreement, and more importantly those being held, will get their day in court so to speak. Already suits have been filed and are working their way through the courts asking the Judical Branch to better outline the restrictions and ability of the Executive Branch during this War on Terror.<br />
