	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Furthermore, "We, the citizens," legalize nothing. The citizens do not have the power to legalize a damn thing<hr size="1" /></blockquote>Yes we do all state that I am aware of have a proposition system where general citizen directly vote on laws. Further our representatives in local, state, federal government are elected citizens. No law has ever been or enacted that was NOT voted on by citizens.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" /> I've checked two major brands of dictionaries and they both say the exact same thing: an oath is a pledge<hr size="1" /></blockquote>What dictionary ... mine come from a dictionary too.<br />
<br />
<a href="http://www.brainydictionary.com/words/oa/oath195250.html" target="_blank">http://www.brainydictionary.com/wor...oath195250.html</a><br />
<a href="http://www.wordreference.com/english/definition.asp?en=oath" target="_blank">http://www.wordreference.com/englis...ion.asp?en=oath</a><br />
<br />
Pledge<br />
<br />
<a href="http://www.wordreference.com/english/definition.asp?en=pledge" target="_blank">http://www.wordreference.com/englis...n.asp?en=pledge</a><br />
<a href="http://www.brainydictionary.com/words/pl/pledge203840.html" target="_blank">http://www.brainydictionary.com/wor...edge203840.html</a><br />
<br />
They are not the same word. And to construe the pledge of allegiance as an oath absolutely incorrect. Try this web site<br />
<br />
<a href="http://thesaurus.reference.com/search?q=pledge" target="_blank">http://thesaurus.reference.com/search?q=pledge</a><br />
<br />
Go to the third entry for pledge, when used as a verb oath is NOT a synonym!<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />No, a citizen must follow them.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>I believe respect is a better term. Martin Luther King respected the rules of law in this country, but he did not follow certain laws. There are occasions were a citizen must not follow a law. However if you meant a citizen must follow them or accept their punishment I will agree with you.<br />
<br />
The 2000 seizure reversed the burden of proof to the government. Before a person had to place a bond of 10% the value of the property and prove that it was not used in the commission of a crime. Now the bond has been eliminated and the government must proved that the item was used in a crime. A meaningful innocent owner defense was added. The "80%" figure comes from a 1991 newstory. I do not argue that during the period of 1984 to 1993 seizure laws were horrid. Do you have any evidence that federal seizure laws have been broadly mis-used since 2000?<br />
<br />
I find your position almost comical regarding police powers in crime. You rail against federal seizure laws but happily surrender your personal freedoms. You would allow evidence if the police violate the Constitution just as long as the guy is guilty. Of course in case where the accused is innocent such evidence would be disallowed. I wonder why have rules of evidence at all I am certain that the police given enough authority can find the correct people of crimes. <br />
<br />
It is impossible to achieve a balance between our personal freedoms and an unchecked police force. Your arguement that the officer should be punished and that will protect us is worthless. It simply will not work. Officers that violate procedure are punished. Our justice system is based on the assumption that the accused is innocent until proven guilty. The person shall not be deprived his rights until found guilty by a jury. This is a great strength of our nation. You seek to weaken it.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
