Go to the third entry for pledge, when used as a verb oath is NOT a synonym!<hr size="1" /></blockquote>"Vow" is though, and under the first definition so is oath.  So?<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />I believe respect is a better term. Martin Luther King respected the rules of law in this country, but he did not follow certain laws. There are occasions were a citizen must not follow a law. However if you meant a citizen must follow them or accept their punishment I will agree with you.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>Yes, that's what I meant.  I don't see how you mean they "must" respect the laws.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />The 2000 seizure reversed the burden of proof to the government. Before a person had to place a bond of 10% the value of the property and prove that it was not used in the commission of a crime. Now the bond has been eliminated and the government must proved that the item was used in a crime. A meaningful innocent owner defense was added.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>What about double jeopardy?  One of the biggest problems before was that even though people won in court, they still didn't get anything back.  Even after winning multiple times.  Helping them win the case doesn't matter if winning the case isn't going to get them anything back.  And what about the billions stolen previously?<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />The "80%" figure comes from a 1991 newstory. I do not argue that during the period of 1984 to 1993 seizure laws were horrid. Do you have any evidence that federal seizure laws have been broadly mis-used since 2000?<hr size="1" /></blockquote>Well to start, I'm wondering why that 1991 story that was cleared up in 2000 reads "March 2001" on a site whose copyright starts in 1994.<br />
<br />
*much searching later*  Ah-ha.  <a href="http://www.lewrockwell.com/orig/felkins11.html" target="_blank">http://www.lewrockwell.com/orig/felkins11.html</a>  I'll quote some of the worst parts, but there's much more to it.<br />
<br />
---<br />
<br />
"The reform bill (Civil Asset Forfeiture Reform Act, "CAFRA") only applies to a portion of the federal government and not to states at all"<br />
<br />
---<br />
<br />
---<br />
<br />
If "the property subject to forfeiture is real property that is being used by the person as a primary residence, the court, at the request of the person, shall insure that the person is represented by an attorney for the Legal Services Corporation with respect to the claim. " By now, you should be fairly well educated as to the workings of our geniuses in Congress and should already be saying to yourself, "I wonder who the hell 'Legal Services Corporation' (LSC) is and if they know they have this new responsibility." OK, you got them pegged ? according to Brenda Grantland in her book, Asset Forfeiture Defense Manual, LSC is a non-profit organization who does not actually have any attorneys (but they can hire them) and, no, they were not consulted before this bill was signed into law!"<br />
<br />
---<br />
<br />
---<br />
<br />
Now, according to the government, if the "value of the seized property is small" (see box), there is no need to go to all the expense of having a trial and all that idealistic stuff ? you just take the property with an "administrative forfeiture" or as it is sometimes called, a "summary forfeiture". Now before you start ranting that $500,000 is not all that small around your house, remember that this law was written by the government and to them $500,000 is essentially insignificant.<br />
<br />
---<br />
<br />
First one must prove that he is an "owner". Trivial? Maybe not. The government's definition of an owner is sort of like its definition of "fresh" with regard to foods (until recently, the government standard allowed producers to freeze chicken as low as 1 degree Fahrenheit and still label it as fresh), it may not jive with what you think an "owner" might be. Without going into all the gory details, I will give just one sentence from the code: an innocent owner must be "a person who was a bona fide purchaser or seller for value". That means that outright gifts such as the Rolex that Aunt Minnie gave you for Christmas does not qualify as being "owned" by you if the government decides to take it.<br />
<br />
---<br />
<br />
---<br />
<br />
But it gets worse. Did the person selling to you subtlely suggest that he may have obtained the property illegally? Did he jokingly hint that he might have acquired it illegally? Did he make a remark that sounded like a joke to you (Like, "Man, I can make you a deal on this property because I practically stole it")? A couple of years ago a business friend of mine was attempting to sell his property. A man came to him showing an interest. They spent several hours discussing the details one evening over drinks and dinner. What my friend didn't know was that the potential purchaser was actually a government agent wearing a recording device and the whole setup was a sting. Later in a court hearing, the government alleged that the agent had sometime that evening hinted that the funds that he would use to purchase the property had been obtained illegally. Further, the government said that my business friend indicated that he would sell to this agent. <br />
<br />
That claim along with another equally sleazy was used as the basis for seizing my friends business inventory worth nearly $2 million dollars. He never challenged the seizure but instead "plea bargained" to avoid prison time in addition to the forfeiture.<br />
<br />
---<br />
<br />
This is all very bad, but I found something far more sickening.  Remember the story about the rancher who was shot-- no, murdered by police after following their orders to lower his weapon while they were stealing his ranch?  They were never even indicted, let alone punished.  Not a one of them.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />I find your position almost comical regarding police powers in crime. You rail against federal seizure laws but happily surrender your personal freedoms. You would allow evidence if the police violate the Constitution just as long as the guy is guilty. Of course in case where the accused is innocent such evidence would be disallowed. I wonder why have rules of evidence at all I am certain that the police given enough authority can find the correct people of crimes.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>Ummm... no.  In fact, my suggestion would likely DECREASE illegal searches.  In the face of serious punishment, police aren't likely to do it nearly as much as they do now.  Further, where did I say the evidence would only be allowed "if they're guilty?"  That doesn't even make any damned sense.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />It is impossible to achieve a balance between our personal freedoms and an unchecked police force. Your arguement that the officer should be punished and that will protect us is worthless. It simply will not work. Officers that violate procedure are punished. Our justice system is based on the assumption that the accused is innocent until proven guilty.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>I'm quite aware they're punished.  That's why I specifically said severely punish them.  I mean something along the lines of terminating them and banning them from ever working in law enforcement again.  Or perhaps even give them a prison sentence themselves.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />The person shall not be deprived his rights until found guilty by a jury. This is a great strength of our nation. You seek to weaken it.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>No, I seek the greater good of the majority.  Which this would probably accomplish, IMO.  If you disagree, fine.  If you want to debate it, fine.  But making things up like claiming I said the evidence should be allowed only if the suspect is guilty... well... whatever.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
